# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: testing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:testing/code-review] Code review differs from related software quality assurance techniques like static code analysis, self-checks, testing, and pair programming.
[src:testing/code-review] Static analysis relies primarily on automated tools, self-checks involve only the author, testing requires code execution, and pair programming is performed continuously during development rather than as a separate step.
[src:testing/code-review] Several variations of code review processes exist, with additional types specified in IEEE 1028.
[src:testing/code-review] The first code review process that was studied and described in detail was called "Inspection" by its inventor, Michael Fagan.
[src:testing/code-review] Fagan inspection is a formal process that involves a careful and detailed execution with multiple participants and phases.
[src:testing/code-review] In formal code reviews, software developers attend a series of meetings to examine code line by line, often using printed copies.
[src:testing/code-review] Research has shown formal inspections to be extremely thorough and highly effective at identifying defects.
[src:testing/code-review] Software development teams typically adopt a more lightweight review process in which the scope of each review relates to changes to the codebase corresponding to a ticket, user story, commit, or some other unit of work.
[src:testing/code-review] Furthermore, there are rules or conventions that integrate the review task into the development workflow through conventions like mandatory review of all tickets, commonly as part of a pull request, instead of explicitly planning each review.
[src:testing/code-review] Such a process is called "regular, change-based code review".
[src:testing/code-review] There are many variations of this basic process.
[src:testing/code-review] A 2017 survey of 240 development teams found that 90% of teams using code review followed a change-based process, with 60% specifically using regular change-based review.
[src:testing/code-review] Major software corporations known to use changed-based code review include Microsoft, Google, and Facebook.
[src:testing/code-review] Ongoing research by Capers Jones analyzing over 12,000 software development projects found formal inspections had a latent defect discovery rate of 60-65%, while informal inspections detected fewer than 50% of defects.
[src:testing/code-review] The latent defect discovery rate for most forms of testing is about 30%.
[src:testing/code-review] A code review case study published in the book *Best Kept Secrets of Peer Code Review* contradicted the Capers Jones study, finding that lightweight reviews can uncover as many bugs as formal reviews while being faster and less costly.
[src:testing/code-review] Studies indicate that up to 75% of code review comments affect software evolvability and maintainability rather than functionality, suggesting that code reviews are an excellent tool for software companies with long product or system life cycles.
[src:testing/code-review] Therefore, less than 15% of issues discussed in code reviews relate directly to bugs.
[src:testing/code-review] Research indicates review effectiveness correlates with review speed.
[src:testing/code-review] Optimal code review rates range from 200 to 400 lines of code per hour.
[src:testing/code-review] Inspecting and reviewing more than a few hundred lines of code per hour for critical software (such as safety critical embedded software) may be too fast to find errors.
[src:testing/code-review] Static code analysis tools assist reviewers by automatically checking source code for known vulnerabilities and defect patterns, particularly for large chunks of code.
[src:testing/code-review] A 2012 study by VDC Research reports that 17.6% of the embedded software engineers surveyed currently use automated tools to support peer code review and 23.7% plan to use them within two years.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] The earliest known work (1989) on continuous integration was the Infuse environment developed by G.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] In 1997, Kent Beck and Ron Jeffries invented extreme programming (XP) while on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System project, including continuous integration.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Beck published about continuous integration in 1998, emphasising the importance of face-to-face communication over technological support.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] In 1999, Beck elaborated more in his first full book on Extreme Programming.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] CruiseControl, one of the first open-source CI tools, was released in 2001.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] In 2010, Timothy Fitz published an article detailing how IMVU's engineering team had built and been using the first practical CD system.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] While his post was originally met with skepticism, it quickly caught on and found widespread adoption as part of the lean software development methodology, also based on IMVU.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] The core activities of CI are that developers co-locate code changes in a shared, integration area frequently and that the resulting integrated codebase is verified for correctness.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] The first part generally involves merging changes to a common version control branch.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] The second part generally involves automated processes including: building, testing and many other processes.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Typically, a server builds from the integration area frequently, i.e. after each commit or periodically, like once a day.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] The server may perform quality control checks such as running unit tests and collect software quality metrics via processes such as static analysis and performance testing.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Build automation tools automate building.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend that a single command should have the capability of building the system.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Automation often includes automating the integration, which often includes deployment into a production-like environment.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] In many cases, the build script not only compiles binaries but also generates documentation, website pages, statistics and distribution media (such as Debian DEB, Red Hat RPM or Windows MSI files).
[src:testing/continuous-integration] CI requires the version control system to support atomic commits; in other words, all of a developer's changes are handled as a single commit.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] When making a code change, a developer creates a branch that is a copy of the current codebase.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] As other changes are committed to the repository, this copy diverges from the latest version.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] The longer development continues on a branch without merging to the integration branch, the greater the risk of multiple integration conflicts and failures when the developer branch is eventually merged back.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] When developers submit code to the repository they must first update their code to reflect the changes in the repository since they took their copy.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] The more changes the repository contains, the more work developers must do before submitting their own changes.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Eventually, the repository may become so different from the developers' baselines that they enter what is sometimes referred to as "merge hell", or "integration hell", where the time it takes to integrate exceeds the time it took to make their original changes.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI suggest that developers should use test-driven development and to ensure that all unit tests pass locally before committing to the integration branch so that one developer's work does not break another developer's copy.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Incomplete features can be disabled before committing, using feature toggles.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Continuous delivery ensures the software checked in on an integration branch is always in a state that can be deployed to users, and continuous deployment automates the deployment process.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend storing all files and information needed for building in version control (for git a *repository*), and that the system should be buildable from a fresh checkout and not require additional dependencies.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Martin Fowler recommends that all developers commit to the same integration branch.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Developers can reduce the effort of resolving conflicting changes by synchronizing changes with each other frequently, at least daily.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Checking in a week's worth of work risks conflict both in likelihood of occurrence and complexity to resolve.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Relatively small conflicts are significantly easier to resolve than larger ones.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Integrating (committing) changes at least once a day is considered good practice, and more often better.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Building daily, if not more often, is generally recommended.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] The system should build commits to the current working version to verify that they integrate correctly.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] A common practice is to use Automated Continuous Integration, although this may be done manually.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Automated continuous integration employs a continuous integration server or daemon to monitor the revision control system for changes, then automatically run the build process.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] When fixing a bug, it is a good practice to push a test case that reproduces the bug.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] This prevents the fix from being reverted and the bug from reappearing, which is known as a regression.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] The build needs to complete rapidly so that if there is a problem with integration, it is quickly identified.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Having a test environment can lead to failures in tested systems when they deploy in the production environment because the production environment may differ from the test environment in a significant way.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] However, building a replica of a production environment is cost-prohibitive.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Instead, the test environment or a separate pre-production environment ("staging") should be built to be a scalable version of the production environment to alleviate costs while maintaining technology stack composition and nuances.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Within these test environments, service virtualisation is commonly used to obtain on-demand access to dependencies (e.g., APIs, third-party applications, services, mainframes, etc.) that are beyond the team's control, still evolving, or too complex to configure in a virtual test lab.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Making builds readily available to stakeholders and testers can reduce the amount of rework necessary when rebuilding a feature that doesn't meet requirements.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Additionally, early testing reduces the chances that defects survive until deployment.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Finding errors earlier can reduce the amount of work necessary to resolve them.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] All programmers should start the day by updating the project from the repository.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] That way, they will all stay up to date.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] It should be easy to find out whether the build breaks and, if so, who made the relevant change and what that change was.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] Most CI systems allow the running of scripts after a build finishes.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] In most situations, it is possible to write a script to deploy the application to a live test server that everyone can look at.
[src:testing/continuous-integration] A further advance in this way of thinking is continuous deployment, which calls for the software to be deployed directly into production, often with additional automation to prevent defects or regressions.
[src:testing/integration-testing] Integration testing describes how tests are run at the integration-level to contrast testing at the unit or system level.
[src:testing/integration-testing] Often, integration testing is conducted to evaluate the compliance of a component with functional requirements.
[src:testing/integration-testing] In a structured development process, integration testing takes as its input modules that have been unit tested, groups them in larger aggregates, applies tests defined in an integration test plan, and delivers as output test results as a step leading to system testing.
[src:testing/integration-testing] Some different types of integration testing are big-bang, mixed (sandwich), risky-hardest, top-down, and bottom-up.
[src:testing/integration-testing] Other Integration Patterns are: collaboration integration, backbone integration, layer integration, client-server integration, distributed services integration and high-frequency integration.
[src:testing/integration-testing] In big-bang testing, most of the developed modules are coupled together to form a complete software system or major part of the system and then used for integration testing.
[src:testing/integration-testing] This method is very effective for saving time in the integration testing process .
[src:testing/integration-testing] However, if the test cases and their results are not recorded properly, the entire integration process will be more complicated and may prevent the testing team from achieving the goal of integration testing.
[src:testing/integration-testing] In bottom-up testing, the lowest level components− are tested first, and are then used to facilitate the testing of higher level components.
[src:testing/integration-testing] The process is repeated until the component at the top of the hierarchy is tested.
[src:testing/integration-testing] All the bottom or low-level modules, procedures or functions are integrated and then tested.
[src:testing/integration-testing] After the integration testing of lower level integrated modules, the next level of modules will be formed and can be used for integration testing.
[src:testing/integration-testing] This approach is helpful only when all or most of the modules of the same development level are ready.
[src:testing/integration-testing] This method also helps to determine the levels of software developed and makes it easier to report testing progress in the form of a percentage.
[src:testing/integration-testing] In top-down testing, the top integrated modules are tested first and the branch of the module is tested step by step until the end of the related module.
[src:testing/integration-testing] Sandwich testing combines top-down testing with bottom up testing.
[src:testing/integration-testing] One limitation to this sort of testing is that any conditions not stated in specified integration tests, outside of the confirmation of the execution of design items, will generally not be tested.
[src:testing/integration-testing] Several open-source tools are widely used to support integration testing in modern software development.
[src:testing/integration-testing] They help validate communication between services, simulate external dependencies, and verify frontend–backend workflows.
[src:testing/integration-testing] Many teams integrate these tools into continuous integration pipelines to improve reliability and automated coverage.
[src:testing/integration-testing] Integration tests that alter any persistent store or database should always be designed carefully with consideration of the initial and final state of the files or database, even if any test fails.
[src:testing/mock-object] In computer programming, a **mock object** is an object that imitates a production object in limited ways.
[src:testing/mock-object] A programmer might use a mock object as a test double for software testing.
[src:testing/mock-object] A mock object can also be used in generic programming.
[src:testing/mock-object] A mock object can be useful to the software tester like a car designer uses a crash test dummy to simulate a human in a vehicle impact.
[src:testing/mock-object] In a unit test, mock objects can simulate the behavior of complex, real objects and are therefore useful when a real object is impractical or impossible to incorporate into a unit test.
[src:testing/mock-object] For example, an alarm clock program which causes a bell to ring at a certain time might get the current time from a time service.
[src:testing/mock-object] To test this, the test must wait until the alarm time to know whether it has rung the bell correctly.
[src:testing/mock-object] If a mock time service is used in place of the real time service, it can be programmed to provide the bell-ringing time (or any other time) regardless of the real time, so that the alarm clock program can be tested in isolation.
[src:testing/mock-object] Mock objects have the same interface as the real objects they mimic, allowing a client object to remain unaware of whether it is using a real object or a mock object.
[src:testing/mock-object] Many available mock object frameworks allow the programmer to specify which methods will be invoked on a mock object, in what order, what parameters will be passed to them, and what values will be returned.
[src:testing/mock-object] Thus, the behavior of a complex object such as a network socket can be mimicked by a mock object, allowing the programmer to discover whether the object being tested responds appropriately to the wide variety of states such mock objects may be in.
[src:testing/mock-object] The definitions of mock, fake and stub are not consistent across the literature.
[src:testing/mock-object] Nonetheless, all represent a production object in a testing environment by exposing the same interface.
[src:testing/mock-object] Regardless of name, the simplest form returns pre-arranged responses (as in a method stub) and the most complex form imitates a production object's complete logic.
[src:testing/mock-object] Such a test object might contain assertions to examine the context of each call.
[src:testing/mock-object] For example, a mock object might assert the order in which its methods are called, or assert consistency of data across method calls.
[src:testing/mock-object] In the book *The Art of Unit Testing* mocks are described as a fake object that helps decide whether a test failed or passed by verifying whether an interaction with an object occurred.
[src:testing/mock-object] In that book, *fakes* are anything that is not real, which, based on their usage, can be either *stubs* or *mocks*.
[src:testing/mock-object] Consider an example where an authorization subsystem has been mocked.
[src:testing/mock-object] The mock object implements an `isUserAllowed(task : Task) : boolean` method to match that in the real authorization class.
[src:testing/mock-object] Many advantages follow if it also exposes an `isAllowed : boolean` property, which is not present in the real class.
[src:testing/mock-object] This allows test code to easily set the expectation that a user will, or will not, be granted permission in the next call and therefore to readily test the behavior of the rest of the system in either case.
[src:testing/mock-object] Similarly, mock-only settings could ensure that subsequent calls to the sub-system will cause it to throw an exception, hang without responding, or return `null` etc.
[src:testing/mock-object] Thus, it is possible to develop and test client behaviors for realistic fault conditions in back-end sub-systems, as well as for their expected responses.
[src:testing/mock-object] Without such a simple and flexible mock system, testing each of these situations may be too laborious for them to be given proper consideration.
[src:testing/mock-object] A mock database object's `save(person : Person)` method may not contain much (if any) implementation code.
[src:testing/mock-object] It might check the existence and perhaps the validity of the Person object passed in for saving (see fake vs. mock discussion above), but beyond that there might be no other implementation.
[src:testing/mock-object] The mock method could add an entry to a public log string.
[src:testing/mock-object] The entry need be no more than "Person saved", or it may include some details from the person object instance, such as a name or ID.
[src:testing/mock-object] If the test code also checks the final contents of the log string after various series of operations involving the mock database, then it is possible to verify that in each case exactly the expected number of database saves have been performed.
[src:testing/mock-object] This can find otherwise invisible performance-sapping bugs, for example, where a developer, nervous of losing data, has coded repeated calls to `save()` where just one would have sufficed.
[src:testing/mock-object] Programmers working with the test-driven development (TDD) method make use of mock objects when writing software.
[src:testing/mock-object] Mock objects meet the interface requirements of, and stand in for, more complex real ones; thus they allow programmers to write and unit-test functionality in one area without calling complex underlying or collaborating classes.
[src:testing/mock-object] Using mock objects allows developers to focus their tests on the behavior of the system under test without worrying about its dependencies.
[src:testing/mock-object] For example, testing a complex algorithm based on multiple objects being in particular states can be clearly expressed using mock objects in place of real objects.
[src:testing/mock-object] Apart from complexity issues and the benefits gained from this separation of concerns, there are practical speed issues involved.
[src:testing/mock-object] Developing a realistic piece of software using TDD may easily involve several hundred unit tests.
[src:testing/mock-object] If many of these induce communication with databases, web services and other out-of-process or networked systems, then the suite of unit tests will quickly become too slow to be run regularly.
[src:testing/mock-object] This in turn leads to bad habits and a reluctance by the developer to maintain the basic tenets of TDD.
[src:testing/mock-object] When mock objects are replaced by real ones, the end-to-end functionality will need further testing.
[src:testing/mock-object] These will be integration tests rather than unit tests.
[src:testing/mock-object] The use of mock objects can closely couple the unit tests to the implementation of the code that is being tested.
[src:testing/mock-object] This illustrates that unit tests should test a method's external behavior rather than its internal implementation.
[src:testing/mock-object] Over-use of mock objects as part of a suite of unit tests can result in a dramatic increase in the amount of maintenance that needs to be performed on the tests themselves during system evolution as refactoring takes place.
[src:testing/mock-object] The improper maintenance of such tests during evolution could allow bugs to be missed that would otherwise be caught by unit tests that use instances of real classes.
[src:testing/mock-object] Conversely, simply mocking one method might require far less configuration than setting up an entire real class and therefore reduce maintenance needs.
[src:testing/mock-object] Mock objects have to accurately model the behavior of the object they are mocking, which can be difficult to achieve if the object being mocked comes from another developer or project or if it has not even been written yet.
[src:testing/mock-object] If the behavior is not modelled correctly, then the unit tests may register a pass even though a failure would occur at run time under the same conditions that the unit test is exercising, thus rendering the unit test inaccurate.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Alternative approaches to writing automated tests is to write all of the production code before starting on the test code or to write all of the test code before starting on the production code.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] With TDD, both are written together, therefore shortening debugging time necessities.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] TDD is related to the test-first programming concepts of extreme programming, begun in 1999, but more recently has created more general interest in its own right.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Programmers also apply the concept to improving and debugging legacy code developed with older techniques.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Software engineer Kent Beck, who is credited with having developed or "rediscovered" the technique, stated in 2003 that TDD encourages simple designs and inspires confidence.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] — Kent Beck, "Why does Kent Beck refer to the 'rediscovery' of test-driven development?
[src:testing/test-driven-development] The TDD steps vary somewhat by author in count and description, but are generally as follows.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] These are based on the book *Test-Driven Development by Example*, and Kent Beck's Canon TDD article.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] List the expected variants in the new behavior.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] pass if the variant in the new behavior is met.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] This shows that new code is actually needed for the desired feature.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] It rules out the possibility that the new test is flawed and will always pass.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] No code should be added beyond the tested functionality.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] If any fail, fix failing tests with minimal changes until all pass.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] In particular, hard-coded test data should be removed from the production code.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Running the test suite after each refactor ensures that no existing functionality is broken.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Repeat the process, starting at step 2, with each test on the list until all tests are implemented and passing.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Each tests should be small and commits made often.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] If new code fails some tests, the programmer can undo or revert rather than debug excessively.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] When using external libraries, it is important not to write tests that are so small as to effectively test merely the library itself, unless there is some reason to believe that the library is buggy or not feature-rich enough to serve all the needs of the software under development.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] TDD has been adopted outside of software development, in both product and service teams, as **test-driven work**.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] For testing to be successful, it needs to be practiced at the micro and macro levels.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Every method in a class, every input data value, log message, and error code, amongst other data points, need to be tested.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Similar to TDD, non-software teams develop quality control (QC) checks (usually manual tests rather than automated tests) for each aspect of the work prior to commencing.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] These QC checks are then used to inform the design and validate the associated outcomes.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] There are various aspects to using test-driven development, for example the principles of "keep it simple, stupid" (KISS) and "You aren't gonna need it" (YAGNI).
[src:testing/test-driven-development] By focusing on writing only the code necessary to pass tests, designs can often be cleaner and clearer than is achieved by other methods.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] In *Test-Driven Development by Example*, Kent Beck also suggests the principle "Fake it till you make it".
[src:testing/test-driven-development] To achieve some advanced design concept such as a design pattern, tests are written that generate that design.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] The code may remain simpler than the target pattern, but still pass all required tests.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] This can be unsettling at first but it allows the developer to focus only on what is important.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Writing the tests first: The tests should be written before the functionality that is to be tested.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] This has been claimed to have many benefits.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] It helps ensure that the application is written for testability, as the developers must consider how to test the application from the outset rather than adding it later.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] It also ensures that tests for every feature gets written.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Additionally, writing the tests first leads to a deeper and earlier understanding of the product requirements, ensures the effectiveness of the test code, and maintains a continual focus on software quality.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] When writing feature-first code, there is a tendency by developers and organizations to push the developer on to the next feature, even neglecting testing entirely.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] The first TDD test might not even compile at first, because the classes and methods it requires may not yet exist.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Nevertheless, that first test functions as the beginning of an executable specification.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Each test case fails initially: This ensures that the test really works and can catch an error.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Once this is shown, the underlying functionality can be implemented.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] This has led to the "test-driven development mantra", which is "red/green/refactor", where red means *fail* and green means *pass*.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Test-driven development constantly repeats the steps of adding test cases that fail, passing them, and refactoring.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Receiving the expected test results at each stage reinforces the developer's mental model of the code, boosts confidence and increases productivity.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] In test-driven development, writing tests before implementation raises questions about testing private methods versus testing only through public interfaces.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] This choice affects the design of both test code and production code.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Test-driven development relies primarily on unit tests for its rapid red-green-refactor cycle.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] These tests execute quickly by avoiding process boundaries, network connections, or external dependencies.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] While TDD practitioners also write integration tests to verify component interactions, these slower tests are kept separate from the more frequent unit test runs.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Testing multiple integrated modules together also makes it more difficult to identify the source of failures.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] When code under development relies on external dependencies, TDD encourages the use of test doubles to maintain fast, isolated unit tests.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] The typical approach involves using interfaces to separate external dependencies and implementing test doubles for testing purposes.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Since test doubles don't prove the connection to real external components, TDD practitioners supplement unit tests with integration testing at appropriate levels.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] To keep execution faster and more reliable, testing is maximized at the unit level while minimizing slower tests at higher levels.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] For TDD, a unit is most commonly defined as a class, or a group of related functions often called a module.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Advanced practices of test-driven development can lead to acceptance test–driven development (ATDD) and specification by example where the criteria specified by the customer are automated into acceptance tests, which then drive the traditional unit test-driven development (UTDD) process.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] This process ensures the customer has an automated mechanism to decide whether the software meets their requirements.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] With ATDD, the development team now has a specific target to satisfy – the acceptance tests – which keeps them continuously focused on what the customer really wants from each user story.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Effective layout of a test case ensures all required actions are completed, improves the readability of the test case, and smooths the flow of execution.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Consistent structure helps in building a self-documenting test case.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] A commonly applied structure for test cases has (1) setup, (2) execution, (3) validation, and (4) cleanup.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] The common practice of allowing a 5-10 percent margin for late execution reduces the potential number of false negatives in test execution.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] It is also suggested to treat test code with the same respect as production code.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Test code must work correctly for both positive and negative cases, last a long time, and be readable and maintainable.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Teams can get together and review tests and test practices to share effective techniques and catch bad habits.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Test-driven development is related to, but different from acceptance test–driven development (ATDD).
[src:testing/test-driven-development] TDD is primarily a developer's tool to help create well-written unit of code (function, class, or module) that correctly performs a set of operations.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] ATDD is a communication tool between the customer, developer, and tester to ensure that the requirements are well-defined.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] ATDD does not, although automation helps with regression testing.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Tests used in TDD can often be derived from ATDD tests, since the code units implement some portion of a requirement.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] ATDD tests should be readable by the customer.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] BDD (behavior-driven development) combines practices from TDD and from ATDD.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] It includes the practice of writing tests first, but focuses on tests which describe behavior, rather than tests which test a unit of implementation.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Tools such as JBehave, Cucumber, Mspec and Specflow provide syntaxes which allow product owners, developers and test engineers to define together the behaviors which can then be translated into automated tests.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] There are many testing frameworks and tools that are useful in TDD.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Developers may use computer-assisted testing frameworks, commonly collectively named xUnit (which are derived from SUnit, created in 1998), to create and automatically run the test cases. xUnit frameworks provide assertion-style test validation capabilities and result reporting.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] These capabilities are critical for automation as they move the burden of execution validation from an independent post-processing activity to one that is included in the test execution.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] The execution framework provided by these test frameworks allows for the automatic execution of all system test cases or various subsets along with other features.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Testing frameworks may accept unit test output in the language-agnostic Test Anything Protocol created in 1987.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Exercising TDD on large systems requires a modular architecture, defined components with published interfaces, and disciplined system layering with maximization of platform independence.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] These proven practices yield increased testability and facilitate the application of build and test automation.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Complex systems require an architecture that meets a range of requirements.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] A key subset of these requirements includes support for the complete and effective testing of the system.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Effective modular design yields components that share traits essential for effective TDD.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] A key technique for building effective modular architecture is Scenario Modeling where a set of sequence charts is constructed, each one focusing on a single system-level execution scenario.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] The Scenario Model provides an excellent vehicle for creating the strategy of interactions between components in response to a specific stimulus.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Each of these Scenario Models serves as a rich set of requirements for the services or functions that a component must provide, and it also dictates the order in which these components and services interact together.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Scenario modeling can greatly facilitate the construction of TDD tests for a complex system.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] In a larger system, the impact of poor component quality is magnified by the complexity of interactions.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] This magnification makes the benefits of TDD accrue even faster in the context of larger projects.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] However, the complexity of the total population of tests can become a problem in itself, eroding potential gains.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] It sounds simple, but a key initial step is to recognize that test code is also important software and should be produced and maintained with the same rigor as the production code.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Creating and managing the architecture of test software within a complex system is just as important as the core product architecture.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Test drivers interact with the UUT, test doubles and the unit test framework.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Empirical studies of test-driven development (TDD) have reported mixed results.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Reviews generally find evidence that TDD can improve some measures of software quality, but its effect on productivity is less consistent.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] A 2013 meta-analysis of 27 studies found a small positive effect on external quality and little or no overall effect on productivity, with larger quality gains but also larger productivity reductions in industrial studies.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] A 2016 systematic review of studies published between 1999 and 2014 found that most studies reported improvements in internal and external software quality, but that productivity results varied between academic and industrial settings.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] A comparative analysis of empirical studies concluded that TDD may reduce introduced defects and lead to more maintainable code, while some implemented code may be smaller or less complex.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] However, an industry experiment with professional developers found that the effect of TDD depended strongly on task characteristics, and concluded that further evidence was needed before determining whether TDD was better or worse than incremental test-last development in industrial settings.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] A later study of TDD process characteristics found that quality and productivity improvements were associated more with small, uniform development steps than with the test-first ordering itself.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] TDD can provide rapid feedback during development because the developer repeatedly runs a growing set of automated tests.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] This can make regressions easier to detect soon after they are introduced, and can support refactoring by providing a safety net for behavioral changes.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Because tests are written before the corresponding production code, the developer must consider the desired behavior and interface of the code before implementation.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] This can encourage smaller units of code, looser coupling, and clearer interfaces, especially when tests are written against public behavior rather than implementation details.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] TDD also tends to produce a suite of automated tests as a by-product of development.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Such tests can be useful in continuous integration workflows, where changes are tested frequently before being merged or released.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] In this sense, TDD may improve confidence in later changes, although passing unit tests do not by themselves prove that the software is correct.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] TDD is not a substitute for other forms of software testing.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Since TDD is commonly practiced through unit testing, it may not adequately test behavior that depends on user interfaces, databases, distributed systems, hardware, timing, security properties, or interactions between components.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] These areas often require additional integration testing, system testing, acceptance testing, usability testing, or other specialized testing methods.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Tests written during TDD may share the same misunderstandings as the production code.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] If a developer misinterprets a requirement, both the test and the implementation can encode the same incorrect assumption, causing the test to pass while the software remains wrong.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] A large number of passing tests can therefore create a false sense of security if the tests are incomplete, overly narrow, or focused on implementation details rather than externally visible behavior.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Automated tests also create maintenance costs.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] Tests that are tightly coupled to internal implementation details, use excessive mocking, rely on fragile timing assumptions, or contain duplicated setup code can become difficult to maintain.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] In some contexts, especially complex brownfield tasks or projects with limited automated-testing experience, the time required to write and maintain tests may reduce short-term productivity.
[src:testing/test-driven-development] First TDD Conference was held during July 2021.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit testing describes tests that are run at the unit-level to contrast testing at the integration or system level.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit testing, as a principle for testing separately smaller parts of large software systems, dates back to the early days of software engineering.
[src:testing/unit-testing] In June 1956 at US Navy's Symposium on Advanced Programming Methods for Digital Computers, H.D.
[src:testing/unit-testing] It featured a specification-based approach where the coding phase was followed by "parameter testing" to validate component subprograms against their specification, followed then by an "assembly testing" for parts put together.
[src:testing/unit-testing] In 1964, a similar approach is described for the software of the Mercury project, where individual units developed by different programmers underwent "unit tests" before being integrated together.
[src:testing/unit-testing] In 1969, testing methodologies appear more structured, with unit tests, component tests and integration tests collectively validating individual parts written separately and their progressive assembly into larger blocks.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Some public standards adopted in the late 1960s, such as MIL-STD-483 and MIL-STD-490, contributed further to a wide acceptance of unit testing in large projects.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit testing was in those times interactive or automated, using either coded tests or capture and replay testing tools.
[src:testing/unit-testing] In 1989, Kent Beck described a testing framework for Smalltalk (later called SUnit) in "Simple Smalltalk Testing: With Patterns".
[src:testing/unit-testing] In 1997, Kent Beck and Erich Gamma developed and released JUnit, a unit test framework that became popular with Java developers.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Google embraced automated testing around 2005–2006.
[src:testing/unit-testing] A unit is defined as a single behaviour exhibited by the system under test (SUT), usually corresponding to a requirement.
[src:testing/unit-testing] While a unit may correspond to a single function or module (in procedural programming) or a single method or class (in object-oriented programming), functions/methods and modules/classes do not necessarily correspond to units.
[src:testing/unit-testing] From the system requirements perspective only the perimeter of the system is relevant, thus only entry points to externally visible system behaviours define units.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit tests can be performed manually or via automated test execution.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Automated tests include benefits such as: running tests often, running tests without staffing cost, and consistent and repeatable testing.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Testing is often performed by the programmer who writes and modifies the code under test.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit testing may be viewed as part of the process of writing code.
[src:testing/unit-testing] During development, a programmer may code criteria, or results that are known to be good, into the test to verify the unit's correctness.
[src:testing/unit-testing] During test execution, frameworks log tests that fail any criterion and report them in a summary.
[src:testing/unit-testing] For this, the most commonly used approach is test - function - expected value.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Test cases underlie testing that is methodical rather than haphazard.
[src:testing/unit-testing] A battery of test cases can be built to produce the desired coverage of the software being tested.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Formally defined test cases allow the same tests to be run repeatedly against successive versions of the software, allowing for effective and consistent regression testing.
[src:testing/unit-testing] A test double is software used in software test automation that satisfies a dependency so that the test need not depend on production code.
[src:testing/unit-testing] A test double provides functionality via an interface that the software under test cannot distinguish from production code.
[src:testing/unit-testing] A parameterized test is a test that accepts a set of values that can be used to enable the test to run with multiple, different input values.
[src:testing/unit-testing] A testing framework that supports parametrized tests supports a way to encode parameter sets and to run the test with each set.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Use of parametrized tests can reduce test code duplication.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Parameterized tests are supported by TestNG, JUnit, XUnit and NUnit, as well as in various JavaScript test frameworks.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Parameters for the unit tests may be coded manually or in some cases are automatically generated by the test framework.
[src:testing/unit-testing] In recent years support was added for writing more powerful (unit) tests, leveraging the concept of theories, test cases that execute the same steps, but using test data generated at runtime, unlike regular parameterized tests that use the same execution steps with input sets that are pre-defined.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Test code needs access to the code it is testing, but testing should not compromise normal design goals such as information hiding, encapsulation and the separation of concerns.
[src:testing/unit-testing] To enable access to code not exposed in the external API, unit tests can be located in the same project or module as the code being tested.
[src:testing/unit-testing] In object oriented design this still may not provide access to private data and methods.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Therefore, extra work may be necessary for unit tests.
[src:testing/unit-testing] In Java and other languages, a developer can use reflection to access private fields and methods.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Alternatively, an inner class can be used to hold the unit tests so they have visibility of the enclosing class's members and attributes.
[src:testing/unit-testing] In the .NET Framework and some other programming languages, partial classes may be used to expose private methods and data for the tests to access.
[src:testing/unit-testing] It is important that code solely for accommodating tests does not remain in the production code.
[src:testing/unit-testing] In C and other languages, compiler directives such as `#if DEBUG ... #endif` can be placed around such additional classes and indeed all other test-related code to prevent them being compiled into the released code.
[src:testing/unit-testing] This means the released code is not exactly the same as what was unit tested.
[src:testing/unit-testing] The regular running of fewer but more comprehensive, end-to-end, integration tests on the final release build can ensure (among other things) that no production code exists that subtly relies on aspects of the test harness.
[src:testing/unit-testing] There is some debate among developers, as to whether it is wise to test private methods and data anyway.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Some argue that private members are a mere implementation detail that may change, and should be allowed to do so without breaking numbers of tests.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Thus it should be sufficient to test any class through its public interface or through its subclass interface, which some languages call the "protected" interface.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Others say that crucial aspects of functionality may be implemented in private methods and testing them directly offers advantage of smaller and more direct unit tests.
[src:testing/unit-testing] In test-driven development (TDD), unit tests are written before the related production code is written.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Starting with a failing test, then adds *just enough* production code to make the test pass, then refactors the code as makes sense and then repeats by adding another failing test.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit testing is intended to ensure that the units meet their design and behave as intended.
[src:testing/unit-testing] By writing tests first for the smallest testable units, then the compound behaviors between those, one can build up comprehensive tests for complex applications.
[src:testing/unit-testing] One goal of unit testing is to isolate each part of the program and show that the individual parts are correct.
[src:testing/unit-testing] A unit test provides a strict, written contract that the piece of code must satisfy.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit testing finds problems early in the development cycle.
[src:testing/unit-testing] This includes both bugs in the programmer's implementation and flaws or missing parts of the specification for the unit.
[src:testing/unit-testing] The process of writing a thorough set of tests forces the author to think through inputs, outputs, and error conditions, and thus more crisply define the unit's desired behavior.
[src:testing/unit-testing] The cost of finding a bug before coding begins or when the code is first written is considerably lower than the cost of detecting, identifying, and correcting the bug later.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Bugs in released code may also cause costly problems for the end-users of the software.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Code can be impossible or difficult to unit test if poorly written, thus unit testing can force developers to structure functions and objects in better ways.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit testing enables more frequent releases in software development.
[src:testing/unit-testing] By testing individual components in isolation, developers can quickly identify and address issues, leading to faster iteration and release cycles.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit testing allows the programmer to refactor code or upgrade system libraries at a later date, and make sure the module still works correctly (e.g., in regression testing).
[src:testing/unit-testing] The procedure is to write test cases for all functions and methods so that whenever a change causes a fault, it can be identified quickly.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit tests detect changes which may break a design contract.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit testing may reduce uncertainty in the units themselves and can be used in a bottom-up testing style approach.
[src:testing/unit-testing] By testing the parts of a program first and then testing the sum of its parts, integration testing becomes much easier.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Some programmers contend that unit tests provide a form of documentation of the code.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Developers wanting to learn what functionality is provided by a unit, and how to use it, can review the unit tests to gain an understanding of it.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Test cases can embody characteristics that are critical to the success of the unit.
[src:testing/unit-testing] These characteristics can indicate appropriate/inappropriate use of a unit as well as negative behaviors that are to be trapped by the unit.
[src:testing/unit-testing] A test case documents these critical characteristics, although many software development environments do not rely solely upon code to document the product in development.
[src:testing/unit-testing] In some processes, the act of writing tests and the code under test, plus associated refactoring, may take the place of formal design.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Each unit test can be seen as a design element specifying classes, methods, and observable behavior.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Testing will not catch every error in the program, because it cannot evaluate every execution path in any but the most trivial programs.
[src:testing/unit-testing] This problem is a superset of the halting problem, which is undecidable.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Additionally, unit testing by definition only tests the functionality of the units themselves.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Therefore, it will not catch integration errors or broader system-level errors (such as functions performed across multiple units, or non-functional test areas such as performance).
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit testing should be done in conjunction with other software testing activities, as they can only show the presence or absence of particular errors; they cannot prove a complete absence of errors.
[src:testing/unit-testing] To guarantee correct behavior for every execution path and every possible input, and ensure the absence of errors, other techniques are required, namely the application of formal methods to prove that a software component has no unexpected behavior.
[src:testing/unit-testing] An elaborate hierarchy of unit tests does not equal integration testing.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Integration with peripheral units should be included in integration tests, but not in unit tests.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Integration testing typically still relies heavily on humans testing manually; high-level or global-scope testing can be difficult to automate, such that manual testing often appears faster and cheaper.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Software testing is a combinatorial problem.
[src:testing/unit-testing] For example, every Boolean decision statement requires at least two tests: one with an outcome of "true" and one with an outcome of "false".
[src:testing/unit-testing] As a result, for every line of code written, programmers often need 3 to 5 lines of test code.
[src:testing/unit-testing] This obviously takes time and its investment may not be worth the effort.
[src:testing/unit-testing] There are problems that cannot easily be tested at all – for example those that are nondeterministic or involve multiple threads.
[src:testing/unit-testing] In addition, code for a unit test is as likely to be buggy as the code it is testing.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Another challenge related to writing the unit tests is the difficulty of setting up realistic and useful tests.
[src:testing/unit-testing] It is necessary to create relevant initial conditions so the part of the application being tested behaves like part of the complete system.
[src:testing/unit-testing] If these initial conditions are not set correctly, the test will not be exercising the code in a realistic context, which diminishes the value and accuracy of unit test results.
[src:testing/unit-testing] To obtain the intended benefits from unit testing, rigorous discipline is needed throughout the software development process.
[src:testing/unit-testing] It is essential to keep careful records not only of the tests that have been performed, but also of all changes that have been made to the source code of this or any other unit in the software.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Use of a version control system is essential.
[src:testing/unit-testing] If a later version of the unit fails a particular test that it had previously passed, the version-control software can provide a list of the source code changes (if any) that have been applied to the unit since that time.
[src:testing/unit-testing] It is also essential to implement a sustainable process for ensuring that test case failures are reviewed regularly and addressed immediately.
[src:testing/unit-testing] If such a process is not implemented and ingrained into the team's workflow, the application will evolve out of sync with the unit test suite, increasing false positives and reducing the effectiveness of the test suite.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit testing embedded system software presents challenges because the software is being developed on a different platform than the one it will eventually run on, making it difficult to run a test program in the actual deployment environment, as is possible with desktop programs.
[src:testing/unit-testing] Unit tests tend to be easiest when a method has input parameters and some output.
[src:testing/unit-testing] It is not as easy to create unit tests when a major function of the method is to interact with something external to the application.
[src:testing/unit-testing] For example, a method that will work with a database might require a mock up of database interactions to be created, which probably won't be as comprehensive as the real database interactions.
